## Overview

A Python package to perform queries and exploit the data available on [BioGateway](https://biogateway.eu/).

BioGateway is an knowledge base built with RDF graphs that integrates a total of 38 resources, including biological databases and controlled vocabularies such as ontologies. This collection covers multiple biological domains of interest, as well as the relationships between them, providing a powerful resource for users to query data in the context of systems biology and subfields like the gene regulation. 

[BioGateway](https://biogateway.eu/) is available for use through its last instance in one [endpoint](https://2407.biogateway.eu/sparql). The queries in the endpoint must be built using the SPARQL query language, and require basic knowledge of the KG schema. Details about this schema can be found here. A [SPARQL tutorial](https://github.com/juan-mulero/cisreg/blob/f1ea81bd3791cec60f0d9d3b4647bf5eefd4df64/SPARQL_Tutorial.pdf) is also available. To jump this gap for potential users, the following Python package was developed to provide users a programmatic access. In this way, we allow users a more user-friendly access to the data, which avoids users to delve into the network schema, as well as SPARQL skills.

We also invite users to use [INTUITION](https://semantics.inf.um.es/intuition/), a webtool that also allows users to build BioGateway queries through an interactive interface. This webtool also has a tutorial for new users and more advanced users, as well as ilustrative use cases. We also encourage users to employ the [BioGateway App](https://biogateway.eu/app/), a Cytoscape plugin designed to provide easy query access to the BioGateway RDF triple store.


